<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-116-106 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 019 094</DOCID><JOURNAL>IBM System User  July 1991 v12 n7 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Making the break into GUIs; taking advantage of graphical userinterfaces does not necessarily mean chucking out old software.andO;(contains related articles on products and GUI benefits)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mancey, Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Adding a graphical user interface (GUI) can improve thefunctionality of a company's computer system and gain acceptanceamong system users that were previously discouraged by difficultcommand procedures.andP;  The problems involved with GUIs includeavailability, compatibility and cost, which is estimated to be oneand a half times the price of each microcomputer.andP;  A large companyinvestment in hardware and customized software may retard the moveto GUIs; highly-specialized programs may have to be programmedfrom scratch.andP;  Some companies are able to apply GUI front-ends totheir existing applications; packaged GUI software can be added tomainframe systems without changing the underlying applications.andO;This method requires replacing dumb terminals with microcomputers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceMicrocomputersMainframe ComputersCustom SystemsBusinessUser NeedsProductivity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>